Due to the high length-to-thickness ratio of the cell, in-plane indentation without any lateral support would lead to the global buckling of the pouch cell. In an attempt to mimic the lateral support of a pouch cell comprised in a battery pack, three cells are rigidly constrained within a custom-made frame (Fig. 1e), while the indenter (
R = 2.5 m m
) is positioned in the center of the middle cell (specimen). Note that the diameter of the smallest indenter is equal to the cell thickness. The indentations are performed in the center of the lateral surfaces (x-z and y-z planes in Fig. 1b).

3D-DIC shows that the slope change is correlated with the motion of the cell surface. Fig. 9 shows the vertical displacement of the top surface during an indentation with a punch of 10 mm radius. Snapshots are taken for a punch displacement of (b) 0.5 mm, (c) 1 mm and (d) 1.76 mm (onset of short circuit). To gain quantitative information regarding the cell displacement, a plane is fitted to the cell surface using 3D-DIC for all experiments. The flatness control tolerance (i.e. the maximum absolute distance for the surface to the fitted plane) is less than 0.4 mm (see Fig. 10 b), indicating that the surface remains planar, while the angle to the vertical direction (Fig. 10c) remains less than 2.5°, indicating a vertical motion of the cell top surface. It is noted that those maximum values are reported for the largest indenter (
R = 50 m m
), while much smaller discrepancies (deviation of less than 0.15 mm and angular deviation less than 0.5°) are observed with radii lower than 25 mm. In those cases, no noticeable changes in the flatness nor in the angle are observed during the indentation experiments.

Fig. 19
 a,c,e show the evolution of the stress profile for a displacement of 0.5 mm, 1 mm and 1.76 mm (onset of short circuit) for an experiment with a 10 mm radius punch. As the experiment proceeds, the stress increases in a conical region under the indenter. The flat region at the bottom of the cell increases its diameter during the indentation, which deviates from the experimentally-observed deformation mechanism. Similar observations hold true for the cylindrical indentation (Fig. 19 b,d,f) at increasing displacement level (discussed in section 4.1.2) and for different radii (Fig. 20
). The cell angular rotation is around 3.7° at the end of the simulation for all radii, instead of the increasing from 2° to 3° with increasing indenter radius.
